         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translations</head>
            <div type="translation" resp="#edd" xml:lang="en"><p><supplied reason="subaudible">Tomb of</supplied> Pupha</p></div>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>For the tomb see Ghazal, loc. cit., with a plate which, however, obscures the final letter 
               (not seen by Ghazal) and suggests that there may have been an additional letter at the beginning, perhaps from a date.</p>
            <p> It is now established that the deceased was a woman, buried in the cavity with which the inscription is probably associated;
               her name, therefore, was Πούφα, not the masculine Πουφᾶϲ as in LGPN <ref target="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-61924">V1-61924</ref>.</p>
            <p>For two further inscriptions found in this group of rock-cut tombs, see <ref type="inscription" n="B.48">B.48</ref> and <ref type="inscription" n="B.49">B.49</ref>.</p>
         </div>
         
